  "prompt": "What is the difference between a valve and a port?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison between valves and ports:\n\nValve:\n- A mechanical device that controls the flow of fluids or gases\n- Can open, close, or regulate the passage of a substance through a pipe or passage\n- Has moving parts like a gate, disc, or plug that can be manipulated\n- Used to control direction, pressure, or volume of flow\n- Examples include ball valves, gate valves, and check valves\n\nPort:\n- An opening or connection point in a system\n- Provides an access point for fluid, gas, electrical signals, or data\n- Generally stationary and does not have moving parts\n- Serves as an interface or entry/exit point\n- Examples include hydraulic ports, electrical ports, USB ports, network ports\n\nKey differences:\n- Valves actively control flow, while ports are passive connection points\n- Valves have moving mechanical components, ports are typically fixed\n- Valves regulate flow, ports provide access or connection\n- Valves can start/stop or adjust flow, ports simply allow passage",
